activity.p:
Once we have the relationship established, we can then move to plug in the variables. If we are told that
"Bob has 5 rocks" then we can set b = 5 and solve: 

	\begin{aligned}
		a \amp = b + 3 \\
		5 \amp = b + 3 \amp \eqnspacer \amp \text{Substitute $a = 5$} \\
		b \amp = 2 \amp \amp \text{Subtract $3$ from both sides} 
	\end{aligned}

Or we are told that "Alice has rocks" then we can set a = 5 and solve: 

	\begin{aligned}
		a \amp = b + 3 \\
		5 \amp = b + 3 \amp \eqnspacer \amp \text{Substitute $a = 5$} \\
		b \amp = 2 \amp \amp \text{Subtract $3$ from both sides} 
	\end{aligned}

p.me:
\begin{array}{c}
	a = \text{Annika's height in inches} \\
	c = \text{Carlos' height in inches} \\ \\
	a = c + 4
\end{array}

\begin{aligned}
a \amp = c + 4 \\
70 \amp = c + 4 \amp \amp \text{Substitute $a = 70$} \\
c \amp = 66 \amp \amp \text{Subtract $4$ from both sides} 
\end{aligned}

section.p:
In addition to having mathematical relationships described by words, there are situations where the relationship is described by a chart of values.
\begin{array}{c|c} x \amp y \\ \hline 1 \amp 2 \\ 2 \amp 4 \\ 3 \amp 6 \end{array}
After some thought, the pattern that you will likely see is that y = 2x. And you can check this by plugging in values.
